# React Native Paper Component Guidelines

## Core Principle

**Always use React Native Paper components for UI elements.** This project exclusively uses React Native Paper (https://oss.callstack.com/react-native-paper/) for all UI components to ensure consistent Material Design styling across the application.

## Component Mapping

### Required Replacements

- `TouchableOpacity` → `Button` (from react-native-paper) for buttons
- `TextInput` (from react-native) → `TextInput` (from react-native-paper)
- `Modal` (for UI) → `Dialog` (from react-native-paper) for alerts/confirmations
- `Text` (for styled text) → `Text` (from react-native-paper) with variants
- `ActivityIndicator` → `ActivityIndicator` (from react-native-paper)
- Custom styled cards → `Card`, `Card.Content`, `Card.Cover` (from react-native-paper)
- Alert.alert() → `Dialog` component from Paper

### Allowed Core React Native Components

These core React Native components are acceptable for layout purposes only:

- `View` - for layout containers
- `ScrollView` - for scrollable content
- `FlatList`, `SectionList` - for lists
- `Image` - for images
- `Modal` - acceptable for full-screen layouts (but use Paper components inside)

## Import Pattern

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Paper components
import { Button, TextInput, Text, Card, Dialog } from "react-native-paper";
import { View, ScrollView } from "react-native"; // Layout only

// ❌ Bad - React Native UI components
import { TouchableOpacity, TextInput, Text } from "react-native";
```

## Component Usage Examples

### Buttons

```typescript
// ✅ Good
<Button mode="contained" onPress={handlePress}>Save</Button>
<Button mode="outlined" onPress={handleCancel}>Cancel</Button>
<Button mode="text" onPress={handleAction}>Action</Button>
<Button mode="elevated" icon="check" onPress={handleSubmit}>Submit</Button>

// ❌ Bad
<TouchableOpacity onPress={handlePress}>
  <Text>Save</Text>
</TouchableOpacity>
```

### Text Inputs

```typescript
// ✅ Good
<TextInput
  mode="outlined"
  label="Email"
  value={email}
  onChangeText={setEmail}
  error={!!errors.email}
/>

// ❌ Bad
<TextInput
  style={styles.input}
  value={email}
  onChangeText={setEmail}
  placeholder="Email"
/>
```

### Text

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Use variants
<Text variant="headlineLarge">Title</Text>
<Text variant="titleMedium">Subtitle</Text>
<Text variant="bodyLarge">Body text</Text>
<Text variant="bodySmall">Caption</Text>

// ❌ Bad - Custom styling
<Text style={styles.title}>Title</Text>
```

### Dialogs

```typescript
// ✅ Good
<Dialog visible={visible} onDismiss={onClose}>
  <Dialog.Title>Confirm</Dialog.Title>
  <Dialog.Content>
    <Text>Are you sure?</Text>
  </Dialog.Content>
  <Dialog.Actions>
    <Button onPress={onClose}>Cancel</Button>
    <Button onPress={onConfirm}>Confirm</Button>
  </Dialog.Actions>
</Dialog>;

// ❌ Bad
Alert.alert("Title", "Message", [{ text: "OK" }]);
```

### Cards

```typescript
// ✅ Good
<Card>
  <Card.Cover source={{ uri: imageUrl }} />
  <Card.Content>
    <Text variant="titleLarge">Card Title</Text>
    <Text variant="bodyMedium">Card content</Text>
  </Card.Content>
  <Card.Actions>
    <Button>Cancel</Button>
    <Button>Ok</Button>
  </Card.Actions>
</Card>
```

## Theming

React Native Paper uses Material Design 3 (MD3) theming. The app uses `MD3LightTheme` by default. To customize the theme, modify the theme object passed to `PaperProvider` in `app/_layout.tsx`.

```typescript
import { Provider as PaperProvider, MD3LightTheme } from "react-native-paper";

const theme = {
  ...MD3LightTheme,
  colors: {
    ...MD3LightTheme.colors,
    primary: "#007AFF",
    // Customize other colors
  },
};
```

## Icons

Continue using `@expo/vector-icons` (Ionicons) for icons, but integrate with Paper components using the `icon` prop where supported:

```typescript
<Button icon="check" onPress={handleSubmit}>Save</Button>
<IconButton icon="close" onPress={onClose} />
```

## Prohibited Patterns

1. ❌ Do not use `TouchableOpacity` for buttons - use `Button` instead
2. ❌ Do not use React Native `TextInput` - use Paper's `TextInput`
3. ❌ Do not use `Alert.alert()` - use `Dialog` component
4. ❌ Do not create custom styled buttons - use Paper `Button` with modes
5. ❌ Do not use inline styles for text - use Paper `Text` variants
6. ❌ Do not import UI components from 'react-native' except for layout (View, ScrollView)

## Style Guidelines

- Use Paper component props (like `mode`, `variant`) instead of custom styles when possible
- Keep StyleSheet usage minimal - Paper components have built-in styling
- Use theme colors through Paper's theming system, not hardcoded colors
- Prefer Paper's spacing and sizing over custom values

## Migration Checklist

When updating existing components:

1. Replace `TouchableOpacity` with `Button`
2. Replace RN `TextInput` with Paper `TextInput`
3. Replace `Modal` with `Dialog` (for alerts) or keep Modal but use Paper components inside
4. Replace `Text` with Paper `Text` using appropriate variants
5. Replace custom cards with `Card` components
6. Remove unused StyleSheet styles
7. Update imports to use Paper components

